<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12163k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12163k">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12163k"> 163(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ adzehead ~ <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12163k"><li>FW 169.11 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n12163k">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n12163k">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12163k">MS BL 47474-22v</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:398 <a name="gd3" href="../../FF/fdra/gda.htm#gd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd3.htm#n12163k">Draft: I.7&sect;1.3</a>/2.3</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The apprehension of the Druids may be reflected in a prophecy attributed to the wizards of the High King.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> &ldquo;<mark>Adze-head</mark> <font color="green">[Saint Patrick]</font> will come <mark>with a crook-head staff</mark>; in his house, with hole-head robe, he will chant impiety from his table; from the front (eastern) part of his house all his household will respond, So be it, so be it.&rdquo; <small> J.B. Bury, <a name="JBSP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JBSP"><cite title="source">Life of Saint Patrick</cite></a> (1905) 79</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The specifics of the translation here point exclusively to Bury&apos;s book, which otherwise seems to have been passed over by Joyce. Adze-head (L. <i>ascicaput</i>) refers to the Roman style of circular tonsure, which differed from the native Irish style, the latter being modeled on that of the Druids and extending from ear to ear. See also: <a name="n12176e" href="n12all.htm#n12176e">N12 (VI.B.14):176(e)</a>, <a name="sa0982w" href="saall.htm#sa0982w">SA (VI.A):0982(w)</a>, and <a name="n47a01c" href="n47all.htm#n47a01c">N47 (VI.B.40):a01(c)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
